the secret garden is novel by frances hodgson burnett first published in book form in following the publication in of serial version in us magazine
set in england it is one of burnett most popular novels and is considered classic of english children literature
several stage and film adaptations have been made
the american edition was published by stokes with illustrations by maria louise kirk signed as l kirk and the british edition by heinemann with illustrations by charles heath robinson
great maytham hall garden kent england
at the turn of the th century mary is sickly and unloved year old girl born in india to wealthy british parents who never wanted her and make an effort to ignore the girl
she is cared for by servants who allow her to become spoiled aggressive and selfish child
after cholera epidemic kills her parents and the servants mary is discovered alive but alone in the empty house
she briefly lives with an english clergyman and his family in india before she is sent to yorkshire in england to live with mr_mr_craven wealthy uncle whom she has never met at his isolated house misselthwaite manor
at first mary is as rude and sour as ever
she dislikes her new home the people living in it and most of all the bleak moor on which it sits
however good natured maid named martha sowerby tells mary about the late mrs mr_craven who would spend hours in private walled garden growing roses
mrs mr_craven died after an accident in the garden and the devastated mr_mr_craven locked the garden and buried the key
mary becomes interested in finding the secret garden herself and her ill manners begin to soften as result
soon she comes to enjoy the company of martha the gardener ben_ben_weatherstaff_ben_weatherstaff and friendly robin redbreast
her health and attitude improve and she grows stronger as she explores the moor and plays with skipping rope that mrs_sowerby buys for her
mary wonders about both the secret garden and the mysterious cries that echo through the house at night
as mary explores the gardens her robin draws her attention to an area of disturbed soil
here mary finds the key to the locked garden and eventually the door to the garden itself
she asks martha for garden tools which martha sends with dickon her year old brother
mary and dickon take liking to each other as dickon has kind way with animals and good nature
eager to absorb his gardening knowledge mary tells him about the secret garden
one night mary hears the cries once more and decides to follow them through the house
she is startled when she finds boy her age named colin who lives in hidden bedroom
she soon discovers that they are cousins colin being the son of mr and mrs mr_craven and that he suffers from an unspecified spinal problem which precludes him from walking and causes him to spend most of his time in bed
mary visits him every day that week distracting him from his troubles with stories of the moor dickon and his animals and the secret garden
mary finally confides that she has access to the secret garden and colin asks to see it
colin is put into his wheelchair and brought outside into the secret garden
it is the first time he has been outdoors for years
while in the garden the children look up to see ben_ben_weatherstaff_ben_weatherstaff looking over the wall on ladder
startled and angry to find the children in the secret garden he admits that he believed colin to be cripple
colin stands up from his chair and finds that his legs are fine though weak from long disuse
colin and mary soon spend almost every day in the garden sometimes with dickon as company
the children and ben_ben_weatherstaff conspire to keep colin recovering health secret from the other staff so as to surprise his father who is travelling abroad
as colin health improves his father sees coinciding increase in spirits culminating in dream where his late wife calls to him from inside the garden
when he receives letter from mrs_sowerby he takes the opportunity finally to return home
he walks the outer garden wall in his wife memory but hears voices inside finds the door unlocked and is shocked to see the garden in full bloom and his son healthy having just won race against the other two children
the servants watch stunned as mr_mr_craven and colin walk back to the manor together
the secret garden at misselthwaite manor is the site of both the near destruction and the subsequent regeneration of family
another theme is when thing is neglected it withers and dies but when it is worked on and cared for it thrives as mary and colin do
the book working title was mistress mary in reference to the english nursery rhyme mary mary quite contrary
parts of it were written during burnett visits to buile hill park the secret garden was first serialised starting in autumn in the american magazine publication aimed at adults
the entire book was first published in summer by frederick stokes in new york and published that year by william heinemann in london
as result several abridged and unabridged editions were published during the late and early such as the full color illustrated edition from david godine publisher in
maytham hall in kent england where burnett lived for number of years during her marriage is often cited as the inspiration for the book setting
burnett kept an extensive garden including an impressive rose garden
however it has been noted that besides the garden maytham hall and misselthwaite manor are physically very different
inga moore abridged edition of illustrated by her is arranged so that line of the text also serves as caption to picture
marketing to both adult and juvenile audiences may have had an effect on its early reception the book was not as celebrated as burnett previous works during her lifetime
the secret garden paled in comparison to the popularity of burnett other works for long period
tracing the book revival from almost complete eclipse at the time of burnett death in anne lundin noted that the author obituary notices all remarked on little lord fauntleroy and passed over the secret garden in silence
with the rise of scholarly work in children literature over the past quarter century the secret garden has risen steadily in prominence
it is often noted as one of the best children books of the twentieth century
in it ranked number in the big read survey of the british public by the bbc to identify the nation best loved novel not children novel
based on online poll the s national education association named it one of teachers top books for children
in it was ranked number among all time children novels in survey published by school library journal monthly with primarily s
little princess was ranked number and little lord fauntleroy did not make the top
jeffrey masson considers the secret garden one of the greatest books ever written for children
in an oblique compliment barbara sleigh has her title character reading the secret garden on the train at the beginning of her children novel jessamy
